ğŸ§  Why Forms Are Important?

Forms are used in:

* Login pages
* Signup forms
* Search bars
* Contact forms
* Checkout pages

React handles forms differently from plain HTML.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Controlled Components (Most Important â­)

A **controlled component** is a form input whose value is controlled by **React state**.

ğŸ“Œ React controls the form data
ğŸ“Œ State is the single source of truth

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§¾ Controlled Input Example

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function LoginForm() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");

  return (
    <input
      type="email"
      value={email}
      onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

âœ” Input value comes from state
âœ” onChange updates state

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Controlled Form Example

```jsx
function SignupForm() {
  const [formData, setFormData] = useState({
    name: "",
    email: ""
  });

  const handleChange = (e) => {
    setFormData({
      ...formData,
      [e.target.name]: e.target.value
    });
  };

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log(formData);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input
        name="name"
        value={formData.name}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />

      <input
        name="email"
        value={formData.email}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />

      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Always use `preventDefault()`
ğŸ“Œ Spread operator to update object state

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Uncontrolled Components

An **uncontrolled component** stores data inside the DOM itself.

ğŸ“Œ Uses `ref` to access value
ğŸ“Œ Less commonly used

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§¾ Uncontrolled Example

```jsx
import { useRef } from "react";

function Form() {
  const inputRef = useRef();

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log(inputRef.current.value);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type="text" ref={inputRef} />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Value not stored in state
ğŸ“Œ Accessed via `ref`

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ†š Controlled vs Uncontrolled

| Controlled           | Uncontrolled       |
| -------------------- | ------------------ |
| Uses state           | Uses ref           |
| React controls input | DOM controls input |
| Easy validation      | Less flexible      |
| Preferred â­          | Rarely used        |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Handling Different Input Types

Checkbox

```jsx
const [isChecked, setIsChecked] = useState(false);

<input
  type="checkbox"
  checked={isChecked}
  onChange={(e) => setIsChecked(e.target.checked)}
/>
```

---

Radio Button

```jsx
<input
  type="radio"
  value="male"
  checked={gender === "male"}
  onChange={(e) => setGender(e.target.value)}
/>
```

---

Select Dropdown

```jsx
<select value={city} onChange={(e) => setCity(e.target.value)}>
  <option value="Delhi">Delhi</option>
  <option value="Mumbai">Mumbai</option>
</select>
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· Basic Form Validation

```jsx
if (formData.email === "") {
  alert("Email is required");
}
```

Better approach:

* Show error message in UI
* Use validation libraries (future topic)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš ï¸ Common Mistakes

âŒ Forgetting `onChange`
âŒ Missing `name` attribute
âŒ Not using spread operator
âŒ Mixing controlled & uncontrolled inputs
âŒ Not preventing default form submit

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

âœ” Use controlled components
âœ” Keep form state organized
âœ” Use single handler for multiple inputs
âœ” Validate before submit
âœ” Keep form logic separate

